sive, and they require a lot of fuel.\\u201d But for the true barbecue devotees, the work is certainly worth the effort. \\u201cYou typically have to fuel them every hour,\\u201d Raichlen says, \\u201cso you need a big pile of wood, and you\\u2019ve got to split the wood, which is why guys like me like them: They're all about the process.\\u201d\",\"dropCap\":false,\"anchor\":\"\"}","originalContent":"\u003cp\u003eIf youre in the market for an offset barrel smoker, a.k.a. a conventional stick burner, Raichlen says the gold standard brand is Horizon, and this 16 option is a great starter model. A stick burner is typically used for your classic Texas brisket and beef ribs, Southern ribs, and pork shoulder. These take up a lot of real estate, he says, so you need to have the space. A stick burner does not work well on a rooftop in Brooklyn. They're expensive, and they require a lot of fuel. But for the true barbecue devotees, the work is certainly worth the effort. You typically have to fuel them every hour, Raichlen says, so you need a big pile of wood, and youve got to split the wood, which is why guys like me like them: They're all about the process.\u003c/p\u003e","innerBlocks":[]},{"name":"core/heading","order":46,"attributesJSON":"{\"content\":\"\u003cstrong\u003eFeatures to Keep in Mind\u003c\\/strong\u003e\",\"level\":2,\"anchor\":\"h-features-to-keep-in-mind\"}","innerBlocks":[]},{"name":"core/heading","order":47,"attributesJSON":"{\"content\":\"\u003cstrong\u003eType\u003c\\/strong\u003e\",\"level\":3,\"anchor\":\"h-type\"}","innerBlocks":[]},{"name":"core/paragraph","order":48,"attributesJSON":"{\"content\":\"The biggest difference between most smokers is the type of fuel they use, and how hands-off or high maintenance the smoking process is. First up is charcoal, that familiar staple of backyard cookouts and camping trips, which is a traditional, if finicky, approach to smoking. Raichlen calls it his \\u201cpreferred fuel for smoking, with wood chunks or chips added as an enhancement,\\u201d which he loves for its process as much as the end result. \\u201cI'm a live fire guy: I love the act of lighting, building, and attending to a fire, and though it\\u2019s not necessarily the most convenient or easiest option, I think you get the best smoke flavor with that combination of charcoal and hardwood,\\u201d he explains. Charcoal is also used in pit barrel smokers: \\u201cYou generally hang the food from a bar on the top, and charcoal goes in the bottom,\\u201d Raichlen says. \\u201cIt's not quite as effective for smoking, but a lot of people like them because they\\u2019re very affordable.\\u201d\",\"dropCap\":false,\"anchor\":\"\"}","originalContent":"\u003cp\u003eThe biggest difference between most smokers is the type of fuel they use, and how hands-off or high maintenance the smoking process is. First up is charcoal, that familiar staple of backyard cookouts and camping trips, which is a traditional, if finicky, approach to smoking. Raichlen calls it his preferred fuel for smoking, with wood chunks or chips added as an enhancement, which he loves for its process as much as the end result. I'm a live fire guy: I love the act of lighting, building, and attending to a fire, and though its not necessarily the most convenient or easiest option, I think you get the best smoke flavor with that combination of charcoal and hardwood, he explains. Charcoal is also used in pit barrel smokers: You generally hang the food from a bar on the top, and charcoal goes in the bottom, Raichlen says. It's not quite as effective for smoking, but a lot of people like them because theyre very affordable.\u003c/p\u003e","innerBlocks":[]},{"name":"core/paragraph","order":49,"attributesJSON":"{\"content\":\"Then there are pellet smokers, which use puck-like compressed hardwood pellets for fuel (charcoal and sawdust pellets are options, too), which burn in a separate, lower compartment. The resulting smoke circulates throughout the smoker\\u2019s interior and cooks the food that\\u2019s on the grill grates above, kind of like a smoky convection oven. \\u201cAn electric fan controls the temperature, so you get a very even, consistent temperature throughout your entire crop, which is very important,\\u201d says Karmel, who loves pellet grills for smoking. Raichlen, however, thinks they offer \\u201cgreat convenience, with perhaps a little bit less complex smoke flavor,\\u201d when compared to charcoal.\",\"dropCap\":false,\"anchor\":\"\"}","originalContent":"\u003cp\u003eThen there are pellet smokers, which use puck-like compressed hardwood pellets for fuel (charcoal and sawdust pellets are options, too), which burn in a separate, lower compartment. The resulting smoke circulates throughout the smokers interior and cooks the food thats on the grill grates above, kind of like a smoky convection oven. An electric fan controls the temperature, so you get a very even, consistent temperature throughout your entire crop, which is very important, says Karmel, who loves pellet grills for smoking. Raichlen, however, thinks they offer great convenience, with perhaps a little bit less complex smoke flavor, when compared to charcoal.\u003c/p\u003e","innerBlocks":[]},{"name":"core/paragraph","order":50,"attributesJSON":"{\"content\":\"Electric smokers use metal heating elements, with wood pucks for the smoke element. \\u201cThe real advantage is convenience since you can set the temperature and time\\u201d instead of doting constantly on its progress, Raichlen explains. He finds, however, that with electric models, \\u201cthe smoke flavor is not quite as good, pronounced, or complex as a wood chip or chunk-and-charcoal combination.\\u201d Propane smokers, also called gas smokers, \\u201cwork on the same principle,\\u201d Raichlen says, \\u201cby using a heated burner to ignite.\\u201d It\\u2019s easier to control the temperature, and the preheating times are speedier on propane and electric models versus the charcoal or pellet versions.\",\"dropCap\":false,\"anchor\":\"\"}","originalContent":"\u003cp\u003eElectric smokers use metal heating elements, with wood pucks for the smoke element. The real advantage is convenience since you can set the temperature and time instead of doting constantly on its progress, Raichlen explains. He finds, however, that with electric models, the smoke flavor is not quite as good, pronounced, or complex as a wood chip or chunk-and-charcoal combination. Propane smokers, also called gas smokers, work on the same principle, Raichlen says, by using a heated burner to ignite. Its easier to control the temperature, and the preheating times are speedier on propane and electric models versus the charcoal or pellet versions.\u003c/p\u003e","innerBlocks":[]},{"name":"core/paragraph","order":51,"attributesJSON":"{\"content\":\"Finally, if you\\u2019re already a fairly experienced griller and want to \\u201cgraduate up to the big boys,\\u201d as Raichlen puts it, consider an offset barrel smoker, also called a stick burner smoker. They\\u2019re significantly pricier and require a lot of attention, and the name refers to the fuel type: The \\u201csticks\\u201d in this case are whole logs, rather than charcoal or wood chips. Offset barrel smokers are typically made from steel oil piping and a 16 to 20-inch-diameter barrel, and feature an \\u201coffset\\u201d firebox. \\u201cSome of them have metal boxes instead of metal piping, but they all work the same way: There\\u2019s the firebox on one side, a cook chamber in the center, and a chimney on the other side that draws the air out,\\u201d Raichlen says. Despite their higher price tags and maintenance, \\u201cwhen you get them right, they produce really fantastic barbecue.\\u201d\",\"dropCap\":false,\"anchor\":\"\"}","originalContent":"\u003cp\u003eFinally, if youre already a fairly experienced griller and want to graduate up to the big boys, as Raichlen puts it, consider an offset barrel smoker, also called a stick burner smoker. Theyre significantly pricier and require a lot of attention, and the name refers to the fuel type: The sticks in this case are whole logs, rather than charcoal or wood chips. Offset barrel smokers are typically made from steel oil piping and a 16 to 20-inch-diameter barrel, and feature an offset firebox. Some of them have metal boxes instead of metal piping, but they all work the same way: Theres the firebox on one side, a cook chamber in the center, and a chimney on the other side that draws the air out, Raichlen says. Despite their higher price tags and maintenance, when you get them right, they produce really fantastic barbecue.\u003c/p\u003e","innerBlocks":[]},{"name":"core/heading","order":52,"attributesJSON":"{\"content\":\"\u003cstrong\u003eSize \u0026amp; Capacity\u003c\\/strong\u003e\",\"level\":3,\"anchor\":\"h-size-capacity\"}","innerBlocks":[]},{"name":"core/paragraph","order":53,"attributesJSON":"{\"content\":\"Raichlen recommends considering a smoker\\u2019s diameter and height in relation to what you\\u2019re smoking to determine the right size for your needs. \\u201cIf you're cooking brisket, that\\u2019s around 16\\u201d to 18\\u201d inches across, so you need at least that much space with a few inches on either side to let the smoke circulate,\\u201d he says. But you can also often modify ingredients to comfortably fit a smoker, he says: \\u201cA rack of ribs is around 20 inches, so if you were to get a really small smoker, you would probably need to cut the ribs in half, or else hang them,\\u201d which many taller smokers can accommodate.\",\"dropCap\":false,\"anchor\":\"\"}","originalContent":"\u003cp\u003eRaichlen recommends considering a smokers diameter and height in relation to what youre smoking to determine the right size for your needs. If you're cooking brisket, thats around 16 to 18 inches across, so you need at least that much space with a few inches on either side to let the smoke circulate, he says. But you can also often modify ingredients to comfortably fit a smoker, he says: A rack of ribs is around 20 inches, so if you were to get a really small smoker, you would probably need to cut the ribs in half, or else hang them, which many taller smokers can accommodate.\u003c/p\u003e","innerBlocks":[]},{"name":"core/paragraph","order":54,"attributesJSON":"{\"content\":\"But in the end, for Raichlen, as with Karmel, bigger is usually better: \\u201cYou're going to be so happy that you have a grill with more capacity,\\u201d he says. \\u201cA lot of first time grill or smoker buyers are like, \\u2018Oh, I'm only gonna make hamburgers or hot dogs,\\u2019 but when you see that a lot of these grills are designed better than your indoor oven and cook really incredible food, you\\u2019re going to want to use it more and more and more.\\u201d\",\"dropCap\":false,\"anchor\":\"\"}","originalContent":"\u003cp\u003eBut in the end, for Raichlen, as with Karmel, bigger is usually better: You're going to be so happy that you have a grill with more capacity, he says. A lot of first time grill or smoker buyers are like, Oh, I'm only gonna make hamburgers or hot dogs, but when you see that a lot of these grills are designed better than your indoor oven and cook really incredible food, youre going to want to use it more and more and more.\u003c/p\u003e","innerBlocks":[]},{"name":"core/heading","order":55,"attributesJSON":"{\"content\":\"\u003cstrong\u003eVersatility\u003c\\/strong\u003e\",\"level\":3,\"anchor\":\"h-versatility\"}","innerBlocks":[]},{"name":"core/paragraph","order":56,"attributesJSON":"{\"content\":\"While many smokers serve that one singular purpose, a standard kettle grill offers the most versatility, Raichlen says. If you use a large amount of charcoal, you\\u2019ll get a higher temperature, which is great for direct grilling, but if you opt for less charcoal, you\\u2019ll end up with lower heat, making it function equally as well as a smoker.\",\"dropCap\":false,\"anchor\":\"\"}","orig